{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}} {{Use British English|date=May 2014}} {{Infobox person | name = Ellis Stanyon | image = Ellis Stanyon magician.png | nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]] | known_for = [[Card manipulation]], [[coin magic]], creator of ''Stanyon's Magic'', [[sleight of hand]] | birth_place = [[Husbands Bosworth]], [[Leicestershire]], [[England]] | birth_date = January 1870 | occupation = [[Magic (illusion)|Magician]] | death_date = {{d-da|September 1951|January 1870}} }}
'''William Ellis Stanyon''' (January 1870 – September 1951) was a professional [[Magic (illusion)|magician]] and magic dealer in [[London]].
==History==
Stanyon published and edited his own journal known as ''Magic''.<ref name="Evans 1902">Evans, Henry R. (1902). [https://archive.org/stream/MagicAndItsProfessors/Magic%20and%20its%20Professors#page/n101/mode/2up ''Magic And Its Professors'']. George Routledge & Sons. p. 88</ref> The journal's aim was to‚ 'popularize the Art of [[Sleight of Hand]]'.<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Stanyon|first=Ellis|date=October 1900|title=Introduction|url=http://askalexander.org/display/16596/Stanyon+s+Magic+Vol+01+No+01/2|journal=Magic|volume=1|issue=1|pages=2|subscription=yes|via=}}</ref> It was first published from October 1900 and ran for 177 issues with a break during [[World War I]]; the final issue was published in June 1920.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://askalexander.org/display/21976/A+Bibliography+of+Conjuring+Periodicals+in+English+1791+1983/183|title=A Bibliography of Conjuring Periodicals in English: 1791–1983|last=Alfredson|first=James B.|last2=Daily|first2=George L.|publisher=|year=1986|isbn=|location=[[York, Pennsylvania]]|pages=163|subscription=yes}}</ref>
Stanyon in his journal published a method of escaping from packed boxes. Biographer [[Kenneth Silverman]] has written that the magician [[Harry Houdini]] "accused Stanyon of having posted a bounty of several pounds for his secrets... Houdini dismissed the methods purveyed by Stanyon and others as being nothing like his own, "puny attempts at duplication."<ref>Silverman, Kenneth. (1996). ''Houdini!: The Career of Ehrich Weiss''. HarperCollins Publishers. pp. 65-66</ref>
Magic historian [[Henry R. Evans]] wrote that Stanyon was "one of the most prolific writers on legerdemain in the world, and his hand-books on magic are largely sought after."<ref name="Evans 1902"/>
